      <h1><a href="/" style="text-decoration:none;">CSS by Example</a>: values</h1>
      <hr />
      <p>CSS values are typically declared using a primitive data type, and in some cases, a unit is required in order to determine specific behavior.</p>

<p>CSS values are:</p>
<ul>
  <li>written in plain english</li>
  <li>hyphenated</li>
  <li>all lowercase (except for some special cases!)</li>
</ul>

<p>Here are some primitive CSS types we will go over in this site (note: some of these include units, and some don't):</p>
<ul>
  <li>numbers - <span class="t-highlight">75&#37;</span>, <span class="t-highlight">-25px</span></li>
  <li>keywords - <span class="t-highlight">inline-block</span>, <span class="t-highlight">initial</span></li>
  <li>strings - <span class="t-highlight">"Times New Roman"</span> (not always lowercase!)</li>
  <li>hex codes - <span class="t-highlight">#004455</span></li>
  <li>functions - <span class="t-highlight">rgb(172, 23, 45)</span>, <span class="t-highlight">calc(100&#37; - 20px)</span></li>
  <li>etc.</li>
</ul>

<p>CSS values map to CSS properties.</p>

<hr />
